This runs immediately during render âŒ

âœ… Correct
<button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>


Because:

onClick expects a function

React calls it only when user clicks

Even simpler example (pure JS)
const sayHi = () => console.log("Hi");


Calling it:

sayHi(); // prints Hi


Same pattern:

const increment = () => setCount(count + 1);

React-friendly best practice (important)

Instead of:

() => setCount(count + 1)


Prefer:

() => setCount(prev => prev + 1)

Why?

Because React state updates are async and batched.

setCount(prev => prev + 1);


Means:

â€œGive me the latest value and increment itâ€

